00:01:58.060 --> 00:01:59.060
Thank you.

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:00.060
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: But, you know when I read

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:04.030
the script and when I started doing research
around the subject matter, what I was shocked

00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:08.659
to find is that a lot of Americans, both white
and black, didn’t know either.

00:02:08.659 --> 00:02:14.599
And that’s when it became a real, kind of,
obsession of mine to be both part of telling

00:02:14.599 --> 00:02:18.360
the story and to educate people about who
they were.

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:19.579
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: For you.

00:02:19.579 --> 00:02:20.579
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Thanks.

00:02:20.579 --> 00:02:27.430
I grew up in a very, very small town called
Lagrange Georgia, which is about 45 miles

00:02:27.430 --> 00:02:29.909
Southeast of Tuskegee.

00:02:29.909 --> 00:02:32.680
So there is very rich heritage there.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:38.430
A lot of the airmen have said that they used
to fly over where I grew up and as we were,

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:45.110
you know, maturing as children, these stories
of their bravery would always be told to us

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:46.110
as inspiration.

00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:51.120
So it was very near and dear to me already.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:57.390
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: I first heard, I never heard
of the Tuskegee Airmen until 1989 and George,

00:02:57.390 --> 00:03:02.569
a very good friend of George Lucas’ had
told him the story and, uh, he loved, he loved

00:03:02.569 --> 00:03:08.640
battles, he loved air sequences, he had used
them in Star Wars, the original Star wars,

00:03:08.640 --> 00:03:13.189
and he was, the minute he heard the story,
the minute he told it to me, this was '89

00:03:13.189 --> 00:03:16.829
for me and he had started about a year before.

00:03:16.829 --> 00:03:23.291
It was such a no-brainer because it was just
such a fantastic story about, you know, people

00:03:23.291 --> 00:03:28.060
overcoming the most extraordinary odds, but
also an action adventure story, it had a lot

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:29.060
of history.

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:30.980
And one of the biggest problems that took
us so long, um,

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:33.469
[Audience member coughing]
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: for him to actually come

00:03:33.469 --> 00:03:39.329
up with a way to make it is it was so big
cause there was the Tuskegee part, which was

00:03:39.329 --> 00:03:45.299
an extraordinary story of unbelievable racism,
a tragic part of American history.

00:03:45.299 --> 00:03:49.799
Then there’s the great part of the guys
finally getting the shot, the chance that

00:03:49.799 --> 00:03:50.950
they always yearned for.

00:03:50.950 --> 00:03:54.531
And there’s also, of course, when they came
back they were treated like absolute, can

00:03:54.531 --> 00:03:55.531
we swear?

00:03:55.531 --> 00:03:56.531
[Laughter]

00:03:56.531 --> 00:03:57.531
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: Sure, go for it.

00:03:57.531 --> 00:03:58.531
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: Treated like absolute

00:03:58.531 --> 00:03:59.531
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: There’s kids here.

00:03:59.531 --> 00:04:00.531
Kids everywhere.

00:04:00.531 --> 00:04:01.531
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: Oh, sorry.

00:04:01.531 --> 00:04:02.531
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: All the kids right there.

00:04:02.531 --> 00:04:03.560
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Treated very badly, very
badly.

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:08.909
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: So there’s these three
big, big stories so, um, but it was like,

00:04:08.909 --> 00:04:11.379
“Oh my God, this is just such a fantastic
idea, this is such a fantastic story,” I

00:04:11.379 --> 00:04:16.930
never thought we’d go through the pain to
try get it made for so long, but finally it

00:04:16.930 --> 00:04:20.270
was worth it for us.

00:04:20.270 --> 00:04:22.280
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: Excellent.

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:25.850
So you guys have been out talking to the public
about the movie.

00:04:25.850 --> 00:04:30.940
What’s been you’re experience around their
awareness of the Tuskegee Airmen.

00:04:30.940 --> 00:04:33.913
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Well, I mean, sorry Rick.

00:04:33.913 --> 00:04:42.950
I mean, now having seen the movie, some of
it is anger, some of it is sadness that it’s,

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:45.920
“Why, now, do we know about this?”

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:52.150
Especially for young black people that you
know, we got a letter the other day from a

00:04:52.150 --> 00:04:59.750
school that had attended a screening and they
were angry that it wasn’t part of the curriculum

00:04:59.750 --> 00:05:04.380
and that it was kind of a footnote in terms
of the things that they get to learn.

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:09.650
At the end of the day, what we do with Red
Tails that I’m so happy about is we celebrate

00:05:09.650 --> 00:05:10.810
them as heroes.

00:05:10.810 --> 00:05:16.480
We don’t, you know, the film isn’t about
the brow-beaten black man, which is so much

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:21.810
of what you can see in these kinds of movies
in a sense, often that’s what’s portrayed.

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:27.510
But these guys, one of the privileges for
us was getting to be with Roscoe Brown, getting

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:32.060
to be with Lee Archer, getting to be with
Bill Holloman, some of the airmen who were

00:05:32.060 --> 00:05:37.000
exemplary as Tuskegee airmen during the Second
World War.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:42.011
You know, they never let the prejudice, they
never let the obstacles that they faced, be

00:05:42.011 --> 00:05:47.560
the thing that stopped them from doing what
they wanted to do, which was to both save

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:53.630
the world from, you know, a dictatorship,
and show themselves worthy of respect back

00:05:53.630 --> 00:06:00.110
home and show themselves to be patriotic Americans,
and they did not let the prejudice stop them.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:05.020
So, you know, this is something that as people
are getting to see that in the film, that

00:06:05.020 --> 00:06:10.440
there’s a combination of celebration, anger
and sadness that it had taken this long for

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:12.360
them to be celebrated in this way.

00:06:12.360 --> 00:06:15.090
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: That’s great.

00:06:15.090 --> 00:06:18.500
In watching the movie there was a pretty amazing
bond between the cast.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:23.270
I heard some rumors about a boot camp, or
something else that was done that maybe helped

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.080
forge some of those bonds before the filming
started.

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:27.080
[Laughter]

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:28.370
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: That was the best part for
me watching.

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:29.370
[Laughter]

00:06:29.370 --> 00:06:33.020
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: I still want to choke you
for that

00:06:33.020 --> 00:06:34.020
[Laughter]

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:35.180
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: For those that had to go through
it and those that watched others go through

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:36.420
it, you wanna tell us a little bit about what
you did?

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:42.780
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: I personally went through
boot camp and before meeting George Lucas

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:45.240
and Rick, I hated them
[Laughter]

00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:48.540
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Because they put us through
this.

00:06:48.540 --> 00:06:55.750
When I tell you –. It was a tremendous mental
struggle, physical struggle, spiritual struggle

00:06:55.750 --> 00:07:01.930
cause we wanted to kill everybody that we
saw, and the worst part about it was where

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:08.130
it was set up, it was set up in an abandoned
warehouse, uh, in the winter of Prague, the

00:07:08.130 --> 00:07:11.880
Czech Republic, so there’s snow everywhere.

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:17.730
This warehouse has no heat, nothing is modern
about this and it was how many square feet

00:07:17.730 --> 00:07:18.730
was it?

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.890
It was probably about--
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: It was probably about 4 to

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:22.800
5,000 square feet but there were also no windows.

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:26.490
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: No, no, the warehouse was
about 4 to 5,000 square foot; the place we

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:27.760
slept in was a closet.

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:32.170
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: It was 8 people, the beds,

00:07:32.170 --> 00:07:42.790
the beds were, um, there was about a foot's
length between each bed, we woke up; our alarm

00:07:42.790 --> 00:07:46.570
clock was M80’s shot gun rifle simulations.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:51.280
We had just impromptu 9 mile hikes in the
middle of the night.

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:53.010
People fell out, people cried.

00:07:53.010 --> 00:07:54.480
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Elijah cried.

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:55.480
[Laughter]

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:58.630
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: No I didn’t cry, there
was a lot of precipitation.

00:07:58.630 --> 00:08:02.400
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: in the Czech Republic at

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:03.980
that time of the year, David.

00:08:03.980 --> 00:08:04.980
[Laughter]

00:08:04.980 --> 00:08:07.060
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: He cried.

00:08:07.060 --> 00:08:12.480
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: But it was one of those experiences
that it was genius because they set it up

00:08:12.480 --> 00:08:18.410
where as the Tuskegee airmen had the same
situation, they only had each other.

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:25.240
So there was a bonding experience that you
knew when those bombs went off, that the person

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:28.889
right next to you was gonna have your back
regardless of what went down.

00:08:28.889 --> 00:08:35.210
And that was kind of the trajectory of how
the bond got started, because we knew, you

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:42.610
know listen, they set us up literally in 1940,
the music was period, the food was period,

00:08:42.610 --> 00:08:47.070
the way we had to interact with, there was
no social media, no cell phones, no anything

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:49.150
for over a week.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:54.830
And that bond, it just set us up for not only
being brothers for the duration of the movie,

00:08:54.830 --> 00:08:57.060
but for a lifetime, in my opinion.

00:08:57.060 --> 00:09:03.279
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And also we were very aware
that we were being afforded a completely unique

00:09:03.279 --> 00:09:06.000
opportunity.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:14.630
I defy you to find a movie of this scale with
a, you know, almost entirely African American

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:20.220
cast where we are the center of the story.

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:25.600
You know, it’s not told through a white
person’s perspective, or a white character.

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:32.900
Like Glory did or like, you know, The Help
did, or the Last King of Scotland did, or

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:38.510
Blood Diamond did, you know, the way Hollywood
tells black stories is to do it through the

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:41.340
prism of a white perspective.

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:47.640
And so we were, you know, this is the genius
of George and why we are eternally indebted

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:52.110
to George, is that like he did with American
Graffiti took a bunch of unknowns and just

00:09:52.110 --> 00:09:56.710
went and did it anyway, like with, you know,
Star Wars when no one was making Sci-fi at

00:09:56.710 --> 00:09:58.580
that time, and he did it anyway.

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:04.650
He did that with us, you know, no one was
gonna make this movie with a bunch of no name

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:08.570
actors so to speak, I mean, Cuba and Terrence
are a different matter.

00:10:08.570 --> 00:10:12.140
But largely the film centers around these
pilots.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:15.980
So we were very, very cognizant of the privilege
of getting to do this.

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:18.010
So that was very bonding as well.

00:10:18.010 --> 00:10:19.172
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: It is cool.

00:10:19.172 --> 00:10:22.460
It was cool to walk in; I missed the boot
camp, me and Method Man

00:10:22.460 --> 00:10:23.460
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Oh man!

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:28.650
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Thank God we were the mechanics
and we don’t gotta do all that boot camp.

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:29.650
[Laughter]

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:31.550
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: But as an actor, you know, goin'
onto the set and hanging out with the guys

00:10:31.550 --> 00:10:35.830
when we got there, you know, it was unique
to see these guys all come together every

00:10:35.830 --> 00:10:36.830
morning, they were like a family.

00:10:36.830 --> 00:10:40.290
It wasn’t like people off, you know, you
go to other sets other actors are doing their

00:10:40.290 --> 00:10:43.790
thing, they’re on Facebook, they’re not
really as together as these guys were every

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:47.080
morning at the hotel, eating together, working
out together, going for a run.

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:50.420
I took notice of that; I joined in on the
run, me and Method Man, joined in on the run.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:53.990
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: You joined in on the run,
Method Man

00:10:53.990 --> 00:10:56.660
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Well, you know.

00:10:56.660 --> 00:10:57.660
[Laughter]

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:00.486
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: He joined in, thought about
it, made a rhyme about it.

00:11:00.486 --> 00:11:01.486
It was special.

00:11:01.486 --> 00:11:02.486
[Laughter]

00:11:02.486 --> 00:11:03.486
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: When he forgot his lighter
for his cigarettes.

00:11:03.486 --> 00:11:04.486
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Ah, that’s messed up.

00:11:04.486 --> 00:11:05.486
[Laughter]

00:11:05.486 --> 00:11:08.360
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: But it was cool to see these
guys, it was cool, it was cool to see these

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:09.700
guys connected like that.

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:11.610
You could feel the bond was there.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:13.190
And they did other things like take us up
on the B51s.

00:11:13.190 --> 00:11:14.190
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Yeah!

00:11:14.190 --> 00:11:17.860
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: We all went up on that and that
was, you know, horrific and scary.

00:11:17.860 --> 00:11:20.540
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: So we definitely had experiences

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:25.210
that put us into the moment that you don’t
really get in films.

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:26.210
[Laughter]

00:11:26.210 --> 00:11:27.210
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: Excellent.

00:11:27.210 --> 00:11:28.210
Thanks.

