portraying are right behind camera, rooting

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:14.130
for you, you know, the feeling was unparalleled.

00:26:14.130 --> 00:26:17.120
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Yeah it was a great responsibility
and pride.

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:22.220
My remembrance of being at the ranch with
a couple of the Tuskegee airmen and we were

00:26:22.220 --> 00:26:23.919
asking the questions on, “What’d you do
here?”

00:26:23.919 --> 00:26:27.850
“What’d you think about this?” and one
of the cats asked them, “How’d you say

00:26:27.850 --> 00:26:28.850
hi to somebody?

00:26:28.850 --> 00:26:29.850
Did you give them dap?

00:26:29.850 --> 00:26:30.850
Did you give them a hand?

00:26:30.850 --> 00:26:31.850
Did you bump their shoulders?”

00:26:31.850 --> 00:26:39.160
And this dude was like, “No, we walked up,
we shook their hand and we moved on.”

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:40.910
“So what?”

00:26:40.910 --> 00:26:41.910
[Laughter]

00:26:41.910 --> 00:26:45.380
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: And it was just like, everybody
started sitting up like, “Oh shit!”

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:46.380
“For real, my fault, my fault.”

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:47.380
And you know, like Elijah said, they were
so proud of their story being told it made

00:26:47.380 --> 00:26:50.049
us feel so proud that we were allowed to tell
their story.

00:26:50.049 --> 00:26:53.380
And the two together, it was just you know,
memorable.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:55.150
It was a fantastic experience.

00:26:55.150 --> 00:26:58.140
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: But we also learned that
they’re show offs as well.

00:26:58.140 --> 00:26:59.581
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Well, they got the right.

00:26:59.581 --> 00:27:00.581
They got the right to.

00:27:00.581 --> 00:27:03.559
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: I did so many interviews
with Roscoe where, especially if there’s

00:27:03.559 --> 00:27:14.539
a pretty young lady, he’ll go, “You know
when there was lightening that blows up the

00:27:14.539 --> 00:27:16.470
train?

00:27:16.470 --> 00:27:17.470
That was me.

00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:18.470
I did that.

00:27:18.470 --> 00:27:19.470
Get the record straight.”

00:27:19.470 --> 00:27:20.470
[Laughter]

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:21.470
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: [Inaudible]
[Laughter]

00:27:21.470 --> 00:27:22.470
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Oh!

00:27:22.470 --> 00:27:23.470
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:27:23.470 --> 00:27:24.470
“I flew so low I bent my wing.”

00:27:24.470 --> 00:27:25.470
[Laughter]

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:26.470
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: I was like, “Real—yeah.”

00:27:26.470 --> 00:27:27.470
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: He waited a long time to say
it.

00:27:27.470 --> 00:27:28.470
He waited like years.

00:27:28.470 --> 00:27:29.470
[Laughter]

00:27:29.470 --> 00:27:30.470
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Yeah.

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:31.470
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: You guys think this is a
spectacle to see them right now?

00:27:31.470 --> 00:27:32.470
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Oh my goodness.

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:33.470
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: It’s like you’re a 91-year-old
telling an 89-year-old to shut up because

00:27:33.470 --> 00:27:34.700
they’re too young to talk.

00:27:34.700 --> 00:27:37.400
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: it’s like that type of

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:38.400
stuff.

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:39.400
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Literally.

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:43.020
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: You know, it’s like people
telling lies about who dated Lena Horne.

00:27:43.020 --> 00:27:45.260
It’s like that’s the types of things that
go on.

00:27:45.260 --> 00:27:46.260
[Laughter]

00:27:46.260 --> 00:27:47.260
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: “I danced with her all
night!”

00:27:47.260 --> 00:27:48.260
“No you didn’t!”

00:27:48.260 --> 00:27:49.260
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: “Shut up!

00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:50.260
You didn’t dance with Lena Horne.”

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:51.260
&gt;&gt;David Oyelow: “No you didn’t.

00:27:51.260 --> 00:27:52.260
You didn’t dance with Lena Horne.

00:27:52.260 --> 00:27:53.260
How come I danced with her?”

00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:54.260
“Okay.”

00:27:54.260 --> 00:27:55.260
[Laughter]

00:27:55.260 --> 00:27:59.794
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: So we probably have time for
one or two more questions.

00:27:59.794 --> 00:28:00.794
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: Well, we’re cool.

00:28:00.794 --> 00:28:01.794
&gt;&gt;Paul Snow: Great.

00:28:01.794 --> 00:28:04.940
&gt;&gt;Male #8: How did you feel when you had to
fix the P51 D Mustang?

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:07.560
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: I felt incompetent.

00:28:07.560 --> 00:28:10.350
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: I felt like I didn’t know

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:11.350
what I was doing.

00:28:11.350 --> 00:28:13.900
Again, they gave us a lot of research.

00:28:13.900 --> 00:28:16.090
We were at an air museum.

00:28:16.090 --> 00:28:17.840
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Plane and Fame.

00:28:17.840 --> 00:28:21.890
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Plane and Fame and I dealt with
some mechanics, they walked me around, they

00:28:21.890 --> 00:28:25.470
taught me, gave me big, big books on how to
do it.

00:28:25.470 --> 00:28:28.510
And there was no way in hell I could learn
that quick before we shot.

00:28:28.510 --> 00:28:32.559
But, you know, it wasn’t really about the
plane as much as it was about somebody else’s

00:28:32.559 --> 00:28:33.559
life.

00:28:33.559 --> 00:28:37.660
If I don’t do this plane right it might
cost my fellow man his death.

00:28:37.660 --> 00:28:42.580
So it was very personal to really go through
that plane and be very precise on every part

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:45.230
of the plane to make sure it worked well for
the pilot.

00:28:45.230 --> 00:28:50.240
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Which is why I died, cause
he didn’t know.

00:28:50.240 --> 00:28:51.240
[Laughter]

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:52.240
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: [Inaudible]

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:53.890
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Oh man.

00:28:53.890 --> 00:28:59.250
&gt;&gt;Female #1: How did it feel to be a Tuskegee
Airmen?

00:28:59.250 --> 00:29:02.614
Did it feel like you were a kid again playing
make believe?

00:29:02.614 --> 00:29:05.340
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Well like Elijah said, they
were heroes.

00:29:05.340 --> 00:29:07.770
They flew, saved the world.

00:29:07.770 --> 00:29:16.970
They were young and it was just, it was a
once in a lifetime opportunity, one that we’ll

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:18.630
take to our graves.

00:29:18.630 --> 00:29:24.669
I mean, one of the highlights for us was we
got to take the film to the Whitehouse and

00:29:24.669 --> 00:29:26.330
we got to screen it for the president.

00:29:26.330 --> 00:29:28.200
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: And the first lady.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.890
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And the first lady.

00:29:30.890 --> 00:29:37.370
And what was so incredible, was we had a tour
of the Whitehouse before we showed it to them

00:29:37.370 --> 00:29:42.910
and you know the Whitehouse with all that
history and with all these fusty white men

00:29:42.910 --> 00:29:46.200
and their wigs and things like that through
the years.

00:29:46.200 --> 00:29:47.500
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Rick and George.

00:29:47.500 --> 00:29:48.500
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Old and Balding.

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:49.500
[Laughter]

00:29:49.500 --> 00:29:52.951
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: I cannot believe you just
said that.

00:29:52.951 --> 00:29:53.951
[Laughter]

00:29:53.951 --> 00:29:54.951
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: The movie is over.

00:29:54.951 --> 00:29:55.951
We got paid.

00:29:55.951 --> 00:29:56.951
[Laughter]

00:29:56.951 --> 00:29:57.951
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: We got paid.

00:29:57.951 --> 00:29:58.951
We got a movie.

00:29:58.951 --> 00:29:59.951
[Laughter]

00:29:59.951 --> 00:30:06.460
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: But it was just so incredible
to be in that building with all that history,

00:30:06.460 --> 00:30:13.080
both negative and positive, and then to be
standing in a room waiting for the president,

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:16.299
and for this cool guy to come in and go,
[Clap]

00:30:16.299 --> 00:30:17.900
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: “How y'all doin’?”

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:18.900
[Laughter]

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:21.100
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And you’re like, “Is
that the president?”

00:30:21.100 --> 00:30:22.100
[Laughter]

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:27.179
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And he walked in and Michelle
Obama's giving hugs and the real Tuskegee

00:30:27.179 --> 00:30:28.179
Airmen were there.

00:30:28.179 --> 00:30:29.740
And you know, everywhere you looked there
were black faces.

00:30:29.740 --> 00:30:31.919
You could almost see those paintings going.

00:30:31.919 --> 00:30:32.919
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Melting.

00:30:32.919 --> 00:30:33.919
“I’m melting!

00:30:33.919 --> 00:30:34.919
I’m melting!

00:30:34.919 --> 00:30:35.919
What are they doing?”

00:30:35.919 --> 00:30:36.919
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: Especially the Kennedy ones
[Laughter]

00:30:36.919 --> 00:30:40.640
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: That’s right.

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:46.090
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: I didn’t mean that far.

00:30:46.090 --> 00:30:48.630
I didn’t mean that far.

00:30:48.630 --> 00:30:49.630
[Laughter]

00:30:49.630 --> 00:30:52.281
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: So, you know, to get to do
the movie and then to get to see the

00:30:52.281 --> 00:30:53.669
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: And they served us popcorn.

00:30:53.669 --> 00:30:55.590
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And the little cookies, little
plane cookies in the Whitehouse.

00:30:55.590 --> 00:30:57.620
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: And M and Ms. Remember the M
and Ms?

00:30:57.620 --> 00:30:58.620
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Yeah!

00:30:58.620 --> 00:30:59.620
It was incredible.

00:30:59.620 --> 00:31:04.169
So the combination of getting to play those
men, getting to see them honored at the Whitehouse,

00:31:04.169 --> 00:31:08.050
being there while they’re, having this movie
come out while there is an African American

00:31:08.050 --> 00:31:12.660
president, it’s just like stuff you’ll
tell your grandkids, you’ll take to your

00:31:12.660 --> 00:31:14.740
grave, it was just the most incredible experience.

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:16.150
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Yo!

00:31:16.150 --> 00:31:21.440
All my little brothers, this is not only a
movie, this is a movement.

00:31:21.440 --> 00:31:27.570
This is something we want you guys to take
and cherish for the rest of your lives.

00:31:27.570 --> 00:31:29.510
You’re a part of this as well as us.

00:31:29.510 --> 00:31:32.780
We did this for and with you guys.

00:31:32.780 --> 00:31:36.929
Every day that we did this film we had people
like you in mind.

00:31:36.929 --> 00:31:42.070
And I never would have known that we would
have got to take the film to the Whitehouse.

00:31:42.070 --> 00:31:46.330
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: One of the best things that
has happened to me during the course of this

00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:53.309
experience is the guy who literally put this
bandage on me, you know from the ankle abrasion

00:31:53.309 --> 00:32:00.250
that I just had, said that he took his dad
to see Red Tails and it was the first time

00:32:00.250 --> 00:32:03.960
his dad had been to the movie theater since
he saw Gandhi, thirty years ago.

00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:04.960
[Laughter]

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:05.960
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: He’s got good taste.

00:32:05.960 --> 00:32:09.700
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Yeah, “If I’m gonna see
a movie, it’s gonna be a good movie!”

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:12.300
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: “A movie like Gandhi!”

00:32:12.300 --> 00:32:13.300
[Laughter]

00:32:13.300 --> 00:32:18.320
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: So, you know, I mean that
was like in the early '80s, so that bears

00:32:18.320 --> 00:32:19.320
out what you’re saying

00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:20.320
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Yes.

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:22.919
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: This is truly something that
people feel an ownership of in a different

00:32:22.919 --> 00:32:24.540
way, you know, which is great.

00:32:24.540 --> 00:32:31.860
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: It creates a very honest
dialogue that can evolve into so many other

00:32:31.860 --> 00:32:34.029
things, and that’s great.

00:32:34.029 --> 00:32:39.179
You know, how many times have we heard people
say that men don’t know how to communicate?

00:32:39.179 --> 00:32:46.919
So for a 10-year-old kid talking to his 60-year-old
grandfather and they meet somewhere in the

00:32:46.919 --> 00:32:51.520
middle and get to share amazing stories that,
you know, these stories of triumph are timeless.

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:55.590
Where like you said, whether you’re dealing
with bullying or that father who was dealing

00:32:55.590 --> 00:32:58.720
with some kind of racial injustice, these
stories coincide with each other.

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:01.370
And yeah, I never thought about that.

00:33:01.370 --> 00:33:04.200
It does bridge that gap.

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:09.560
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: And how often do you go to
the movie theater and see someone so dark

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:10.560
and sexy?

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:11.560
[Laughter]

00:33:11.560 --> 00:33:12.560
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: You know it.

00:33:12.560 --> 00:33:13.560
Preach it.

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:14.560
Preach it.

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:15.560
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Like Elijah Kelley in a plane.

00:33:15.560 --> 00:33:22.320
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: Pause, but preach it!

00:33:22.320 --> 00:33:23.570
[Laughter]

00:33:23.570 --> 00:33:29.170
&gt;&gt;Male #9: When you first heard Ne-Yo’s
voice when he was acting did you laugh?

00:33:29.170 --> 00:33:30.170
[Laughter]

00:33:30.170 --> 00:33:34.309
&gt;&gt;Andre Royo: Cut the camera!

00:33:34.309 --> 00:33:37.950
Cut the Camera!

00:33:37.950 --> 00:33:42.970
Wow, this one, he’s on fire!

00:33:42.970 --> 00:33:43.970
No.

00:33:43.970 --> 00:33:48.830
&gt;&gt;David Oyelowo: Rick, over to you.

00:33:48.830 --> 00:33:50.810
&gt;&gt;Rick McCallum: Absolutely not.

00:33:50.810 --> 00:33:55.260
I still don’t understand a single word he
said in the film but I never laughed.

00:33:55.260 --> 00:33:56.260
[Laughter]

00:33:56.260 --> 00:34:01.450
&gt;&gt;Elijah Kelley: There is the 5 P’s.

00:34:01.450 --> 00:34:05.679
Prior preparation prevents poor performance.

00:34:05.679 --> 00:34:11.710
And when you are, we say it a lot in our generation,
when you’re on your grind, when you’re

00:34:11.710 --> 00:34:15.050
knowing everything that you’re supposed
to know, when you have everything that’s

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:19.920
intact, the minute somebody questions you
about what you know, there’s an immediate

00:34:19.920 --> 00:34:22.429
rebuttal in the right way.

00:34:22.429 --> 00:34:26.941
And whatever notion that was had about you
before then is canceled and there’s a new

00:34:26.941 --> 00:34:35.310
beginning right there because you are so intelligence
and you’re so mentally able to talk intelligently

00:34:35.310 --> 00:34:40.750
and articularly, articulate about everything
that you’ve consumed, all the knowledge

00:34:40.750 --> 00:34:47.640
that you’ve had, the bank of hard drive
that you’ve been acquiring over the years.

00:34:47.640 --> 00:34:49.869
You’re on and you’re ready.

00:34:49.869 --> 00:34:54.419
And that’s another thing that, you know,
the Tuskegee Airmen stood for, that was something

00:34:54.419 --> 00:34:59.180
that resonated all the way from just the mood
of who they were to coming on set and knowing

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:02.180
exactly what to do while we were there.

00:35:02.180 --> 00:35:06.160
And again that’s prior preparation prevents
poor performance.

00:35:06.160 --> 00:35:15.450
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Was it hard for you to change
your voice in the movie to make it sound straight

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:16.450
English?

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:17.450
[Laughter]

